Subject:    Top level domains - do not use as bottom !
From:       <a href="?a=95837784200005&r=1&w=2">Paul Mockapetris &lt;pvm () venera ! isi ! edu&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198704">1987-04-08 15:48:35</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926806&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926806&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

If I understand your message correctly, you are telling me that I should
not have a host name e.ISI.EDU because it conflicts with Spain?  While I
might be willing believe that a host named UK.ISI.EDU was in poor taste,
I would also think it to be a good test of the domain naming mechanism.
"Reserved" name components are a bad idea, and single letter reserved
name components are the worst idea in recent memory.

One reason to have a hierarchy is that you can create a unique name by
concatenating a locally-unique local-part to a globally-unique global-part.
Now it is true that you have to be able to tell the parts apart, or in the
names we use tell which end is the root.  It is unfortunate that we don't
all drive on the same side of the road in this regard, but why don't we
just convert names when we cross the boundary?  It works for driving cars.

In mail, we might be able to merge hierarchies and get a cleaner mail
address space.  Reserved names make things dirtier, make innocents into
outlaws (I had no idea e.isi.edu was illegal, and I suppose a.isi.edu
will become so when the Arctic gets a reserved name), and seem to have
no redeeming value.

If there is any response, please copy me - I'm not on the original
mailing lists.

paul

